1.4:
Wave after wave of them came:
what the cutting locust left behind, the swarming locust devoured;
what the swarming locust left, the hopping locust consumed;
and what the hopping locust left, the stripping locust stripped away.

1.6:
A nation — vast and past numbering — has swept over my land.
Its teeth are the teeth of a lion;
it has the crushing jaws of a great lion.

1.17:
Seeds rot beneath the clods of earth;
granaries lie empty and broken;
the grain has shrivelled away.

1.20:
Even the wild animals cry out to you:
the streams have gone dry;
fire has consumed the open pastures.

2.7:
They run like soldiers;
they scale the wall like trained warriors.
Each one holds his own lane;
they never break formation.

2.10:
The earth shudders at their coming;
the heavens themselves tremble.
Sun and moon go dark;
the stars pull back their light.

2.13:
Tear open your hearts, not just your garments.
Return to Yahweh your God —
for he is gracious and compassionate,
slow to anger and rich in covenant faithfulness;
he turns back from sending disaster.
(This is the ancient self-disclosure of Sinai, Exod 34:6, spoken again in crisis.)

2.14:
Who knows — he might turn back;
he might change course and leave a blessing in his wake,
a grain offering and a drink offering for Yahweh your God.

2.22:
Animals of the open country, have no fear —
the wilderness pastures are green again;
the trees are bearing fruit;
the fig tree and vine are full and heavy.

2.28:
And after all that —
I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh.
Your sons and daughters will prophesy;
your old men will dream dreams;
your young men will see visions.

3.18:
On that day the mountains will drip with new wine;
the hills will flow with milk;
all the dry streambeds of Judah will run with water.
A spring will flow from the house of Yahweh
and water the Valley of Shittim.
(This fountain from God's house points forward to Ezek 47 and Rev 22.)
